STUDENT MEDICATION PICK UP

Medication for all Carlisle students will be available to be picked up on Friday, March 20, 2020 from 7:30 to 11:00 a.m. at the Elementary Nurse’s office. District will use the security system in the Elementary Nurse’s office to secure transfer in a no-contact environment.

Parents will be required to bring photo identification to pick up medications.

If parents are unavailable to come at designated time, they can call the district office starting on March 23rd at 515-989-3589 to make arrangements to pick up medications.

post_text:
FOOD SERVICE FOR STUDENTS FOR MARCH 23-APRIL 13 SCHOOL CLOSURE

Carlisle CSD will be offering free lunch meals to students 18 and under during the COVID-19 closure.

The sign-up period each week will be 2:00 p.m. Friday to 2:00 p.m. Saturday for the following week. The Grab-n-Go Lunch meals can be picked up at the High School Commons from 11:30 a.m. – 1:00 p.m. on the following Monday through Friday.

Lunches are for Carlisle CSD students only and are available at 1 per person. Each student must be in attendance to receive a lunch. Students will not stay on site to eat; meals are intended to be taken off campus. Meals will not be billed to students’ lunch accounts during the March 23-April 13 closure period. Lunches will include a meat and cheese sandwich, fruit, chips.

Use the following link to sign up for meals for the week of March 23-March 27. A new link will be sent each week during the closure continues.

https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/LunchSignUPMarch23-27

post_text:
Dear Carlisle CSD staff and families,

The Governor recommended tonight that all Iowa schools will be closed for four weeks until April 13, 2020. In the short term that means our schools are inaccessible except for designated staff. All athletic practices, and activities are canceled effective immediately. Please know we are working through all options for our staff, students, and families and will have more information soon.

In addition, the Governor plans to announce more information tomorrow and we will communicate with you once we know more in regards to the next steps.

We will continue to work with the Governor and Department of Education on a plan for students and staff. As this situation changes rapidly, please know we will communicate information with you as soon as we can that more clearly defines school closure expectations.

Sincerely,

Bryce Amos, Superintendent of Schools

post_text:
School Board Approves 2020-21 District Calendar
The Carlisle School Board approved the school calendar for the 2020-21 school year at its monthly meeting on Monday, February 10th.

The school calendar was developed by the district’s Calendar Committee comprised of parents and district staff. Under the calendar, classes will start August 24 for grades 1-12. Pre-School, Kindergarten & Kindergarten Prep starting on August 31. Kindergarten and Preschool have later start dates to allow teachers to conduct home visit with parents prior to start of the school year. New to this year’s calendar is extending Thanksgiving Break to three days. The last day of school for grades K-11 will be Friday, May 27. High School Graduation Ceremony is scheduled for Sunday, May 23.

The district will continue with early out dismissals every Wednesday at 1:30 to allow for professional development and planning for teachers and staff. Visit the district calendar webpage to view calendar.

https://www.carlislecsd.org/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=701364&type=d&pREC_ID=1134461

Carlisle Elementary Libraries
January 3 at 5:00 PM ·

🤩We are so excited to announce this year's book for our 3rd Annual One Book, One School, One Community is........Charlie and the Chocolate Factory!🥳

✌️There are two ways you as a parent, family member, or community member can join in on the fun!

1. Each week, one of our favorite community locations will be hiding a Golden Ticket. To find it, watch for clues to be posted here on Facebook, in the Carlisle Citizen newspaper, and the Wildcat Weekly. Once you have found the Golden Ticket, snap a picture and post it to your social media platform of choice (Facebook, Twitter, Instagram) and use the hashtag #igottagoldenticket

2. Read Roald Dahl's Charlie and the Chocolate Factory and share a picture of you and/or your children reading it on any one of your social media platforms with the hashtag #ireadcharlie

We can't wait to see your posts, encouraging our students over the next several weeks while they are reading it in their classrooms. 🥰

post_text:
INDOOR WALKING TRACK PASS "Winter Walkers"
The District is pleased to offer the residents of the Carlisle School District the opportunity to apply to use the indoor walking track at the Wildcat Activity Center. The district has a limited number of fob/passes (50) for the 2019-20 winter season. The annual Indoor Track Passes for “Winter Walkers” are available with a $25 deposit. Each Winter Walker will receive a key fob and 2 ID Badge. The passes entitle the pass holder and one guess access to the indoor walking track.

Visit our website for more information.
https://www.carlislecsd.org/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=702494&type=d&pREC_ID=1807959

THE "FITNESS ROOM" IS NOT FOR PUBLIC USE

Bobbi Mc Griff Snodgrass
October 9, 2019 at 7:53 PM ·

Be sure to share this if you know someone who is interested in an easy fall race where they might ring the PR bell. The Half Marathon is flat and downhill from Indianola to Carlisle. Certified course on well protected rail trail, chip timing, the 10k and 5k are flat and fast too. Free photos, medals, shirts, biscuits & gravy, pie, chocolate milk, and lots more to celebrate when you reach the finish line in Carlisle which is one of the friendliest small towns in Iowa. Our Hillbilly volunteers will show you a good time. All for a good cause, see the link below for more info. Only $55 for the Half & $35 for the 10k or 5k. We also offer a virtual race in case the date doesn’t work for you. Use "Ibilly" to get $5 discount. Don't delay, price goes up in a few days.
https://secure.getmeregistered.com/get_information.php?event_id=131134

SCHOOL BOARD VACANCY ANNOUNCEMENT FOR
CARLISLE CSD SCHOOLS DISTRICT #3
The Carlisle Community School District Board of Education announces a vacancy due to the resignation of one of its members, Kyle Chambers, effective August 1st. This is a notice of intent to fill a vacancy on the board. The board will fill the seat by appointment to serve until the next scheduled School Board election on November 5, 2019, at which time a director will be elected for a 4-year term.

The district would like to thank Kyle Chambers for his dedicated years of service to the District as a School Board Director. Kyle served as Board President for the past 2 years, under his leadership the district successfully completed Phase I and continue work on Phase II projects.

https://www.carlislecsd.org/apps/news/article/1062776

CARLISLE MIDDLE SCHOOL’S JOYOLOGY CLUB RECEIVES THE 2019 IOWA CHARACTER AWARD HONOR
The Carlisle Joyology Club was founded by Addeline Morlan, Emily Reid, Madelynn McFadden, Bella Pagel, Sophia Connoly, Leah Olinger, Haley Howard, and Hannah McGraw. Carlisle middle school counselor Ben Barry was the faculty sponsor for the group. Their mission is to spread positivity, acceptance, joy, and kindness. The group is receiving a 2019 Iowa Character Award as the student organization of character from the Robert D. and Billie Ray Center at Drake University.

https://www.carlislecsd.org/apps/news/article/1062412

GRADUATION 2019 WILL BE HELD IN THE CARLISLE HIGH SCHOOL GYM
The Class of 2019 will graduate inside the gym at CHS on Sunday, May 19 at 2:00pm. Doors will open to the public at 12:30 pm. There will be additional seating in the CHS Auditorium with a live stream of the ceremony. Additionally, parking is available at Fareway with a school bus shuttle transporting spectators beginning a 1:00pm and back to Fareway at 3:00 pm.

shared_text:
Carlisle Schools PTO
May 10, 2019 at 11:00 AM ·

To All Our Teachers......

Thanks for ALL that you did today and everyday in your classrooms.
For making a million little split second DECISIONS for the benefits of your students.
For putting your own needs on hold and keeping them the FOCUS of your days.
For PLANNING for them long before the days ever get rolling.
For CHANGING those plans because they didn't fit someone who needed a little extra
For smiling, LAUGHING WITH THEM and reassuring their efforts, trials and mistakes.
For placing your hand on a shoulder that was EXACTLY what your students needed.
For getting down on the physical level of your students because IT MATTERS.
For thinking of a new way to reach a student who wasn't getting it.
You matter.
YES YOU ALL MATTER!!

Again, we want to thank our elementary, upper elementary, middle and high school teachers for all that you do for our students on a daily basis! Pictured our elementary and upper elementary students.
